Platonem). . . instinctis divino spiritu vatibus comparandum. The etymology of ‘vates' is very doubtful. Varro L. L. VII 36, in his na'l've way, derived it from versibus viendis. Moderns generally connect the term with Irish saith. Gr. φάτης, Lat. fari, fabula are different. Mommsen, Hermes XVI 620 note 4 supposes a Gallie origin, on the basis of Sbrabo IV 4, 4 p. 198 τρία φῦλα τῶν τιμωμένων . . . Βάρδοι τε καὶ Οΰάτεις καὶ Δρυΐδαι. On the use of vates and poeta, cp. L. Mulier, de re metr. p. 65—68, Ennius p. 27-29, &yffi-Mun. Lael. p. 165. The purist Tacitus never use's ‘poeta' except in the Dialogus, where it could not well have been avoided. See also note on sapi- entiam c. 5 ext.
